      content: `That place.

The king of hunters glared at the charred ground, his attention so focused it was as if he thought he could destroy it just with his stare.

It always resurfaced when he passed by that place. It started as a tingle at the back of his head, spread down his back, and assaulted his heart. Why, he did not know.

The king had no place left in his perfect body for weakness. He had long ago cleansed himself of all of it. His body, mind, and soul were all honed, sharpened, and purified to make him the perfect hunter. And he had proven, both the mortals and his fellow hunters, that this was the case. He had earned his position as king, unlike the weaklings who had come before him.

The living incarnation of power, a god made flesh, the King of Lorn and of the Blud, the successor of both dragon and man. And he would tear the beating hearts out of any creature that dared vie for one of those titles.

And yet, in that place, it wavered ever so slightly. Why?

It was the place where he had rid himself of one of his weaknesses. Where he had hunted and slain the brood of his mortal life. Burned them alive. Though their remains had long since been claimed by the others, the ground was still charred from its exposure to the heat.

They were weak, and not just because they were small. Because they were soft flesh and scared. And disobedient.

Oh, so disobedient! Perhaps if they hadn’t run, perhaps if they had listened, he would have let them taste the blessed rain and take new form. They would not match his power, of course, but they would have had some place in this new world of the strong.

He felt so regretful at having to kill them. It was necessary. But it would have been better if he had not needed to.

It was that line of thought that caused it! He had to stop it. It was a weakness to think of the past. The weakness of a pitiful mortal man who thought himself king just because other mortals had told him thus. He was no longer that man. He had ascended.

He was no longer that man. Even if he could still sometimes hear that man in the back of his mind. Screaming at him. The screams were normally deafened by the roar of blood and fire coursing through him. But when he was here, the screams could be heard anew.

Screams and sobs. Weak. So weak. Perhaps there was even more he needed to expel. To ascend from perfect to more perfect.

For now, he left that place. On wings molded of his glorious flesh, he ascended through a gap in the ceiling, out into the night. The blessed rain was falling.

He let it wash over him. Purify him. Cleanse him of any taint. Make him more divine.

They were out there. He could sense them, distant but drawing closer. The surviving members of his mortal life’s brood. They were coming to hunt the hunter. Foolish.

One had the blessing. The true blessing, not shallow mimicry granted by the rain. If he bent the knee to the king, he might be tolerated to live. But he wouldn’t. Those with strength do not yield it to others. He would test his might against the king. And he would die for it.

The other he could not sense as clearly, for he lacked any blessing at all. That any mortals at all still remained was insanity. Infuriating. Like a rat infestation—just when you think you have dealt with them all, you find more in your larder.

He might not even get a chance to kill them himself. His sons. The other hunters he had allowed to continue living in his castle would get to go first. But it would be satisfying to hunt them himself. Maybe he could burn them in that same spot as the others.

When he had enough of the rain, he descended back into the throne room. There, he found another who had made himself at home.

It was a bloated thing. The shredded remains of mortal attire clung tight to its bulbous form. He could sense power radiating from it. It had been feasting. Engorging itself until its form could not take even one more ounce of the blessing without bursting. The sheer force it emanated made it a higher-tier hunter than the rest of the rabble. And it thought to use this power to make a play for the throne.

Unforgivable.

It roared at him, its voice shaking the room. He roared back, shaking the castle.

The usurper rushed at him. It raised its claw and struck him. He grabbed the claw mid-strike, twisted, and pulled it until it came clean off the traitor’s body. Then he turned it around and drove it into his assailant’s skull, impaling it with its own claw.

It cried out in pain, but he did not stop. There would be no mercy. He tore every limb from its body and then pierced it through its bloated torso.

Only when the creature was limbless, pathetically wiggling on the ground as it bled out, did he grant his subject the mercy of death with a mighty bellow of flames.

One less traitor. One less threat to his glorious kingdom.

All glory to Lorn.

Long live the king.`,
