      content: `Ulrin’s world was replaced with one of intense pain. His back felt like it had been broken. One of his legs has been twisted the wrong way. His mouth was filled with coppery blood. And then there was the burning sensation all across his body. Guess that amulet had its limits, after all.

He tried to focus, but the pain kept blinding him. Something was pressing against his chest, compressing it and making it impossible to take a full breath. He felt a warm puddle form beneath him. His own blood spilling from his body.

Ulrin knew he was already dead. His body just hadn’t realized it yet.

Somehow, the world came back into view. His mind raced to put together his surroundings. The floor had collapsed from the explosion, and Ulrin had fallen into the chamber below. The dragon skull had fallen after him and landed atop him, crushing his chest and pinning him to the ground.

There was no sign of Gerevin. Given how close the firebomb had been to him when it had gone off . . .

But who he did see was his father.

The king stumbled, dazed, but was still standing. His one remaining eye fixed on Ulrin, and a grin formed on that grotesque face.

“THE PREY HAS BECOME TRAPPED . . . YOU FOUGHT WELL . . . BUT NOW . . . YOU ARE MINE!”

He slowly began to lumber forward, dragging a limp leg behind him. Though the king was badly wounded, he would have no trouble finishing off Ulrin as things stood.

Ulrin laughed with what little air he could get into his lungs. This seemed to startle his father, who stopped in his tracks.

“Some hunter you turned out to be,” Ulrin rasped. “Beaten by your prey. Barely able to survive. Saved by the interference of one of the weak. You couldn’t kill me face-to-face, so you have to resort to killing me while I am stuck. What a pathetic excuse for a hunter.”

“DON’T YOU MOCK ME . . . I AM THE KING OF HUNTERS!”

“Look at your face and say that.” It was getting harder and harder to get any words out, but this was the only gambit Ulrin had left.

“TRAPPED OR NOT . . . I WOULD KILL YOU IN AN INSTANT . . .”

Consciousness was fading fast. Ulrin hoped that this would work. “Prove it. Take this thing off of me and face me like a hunter.”

King Emberlind roared. He grabbed the dragon skull by its eye socket and pulled it up.

Ulrin let in a gasp of air. That was a start. He still couldn’t move and was still dying from a combination of being broken and blood loss. But with his hands free, he could move on to the second part of his desperate gambit.

He reached into his pocket, pulled out the vial of refined Drakenblud meant for him, removed the cork, and drank it.

His body became flooded with ice. No, this sensation was colder than the most frigid ice he had ever encountered, and it was running right through his veins. The sensation caused him to want to scream, but he couldn’t open his mouth. His entire body, every muscle, every sinew, was locked into place.

Then things began to crack. Pop, crack, snap. It was his bones, he realized. They were shifting, breaking, and reforming. His muscles joined them, tearing and stitching themselves back together. It was as if his entire body was being torn apart and reassembled, bit by bit. There were no words in his mind that could adequately describe the agony.

New colors rushed into his vision. New smells flooded his nose. Every sensation became amplified a thousand times.

He thought he could have been lying there a hundred years, given how long he seemed to endure the suffering. But as he slowly regained control of his body and was able to lift his head, he spotted his father still struggling with the dragon skull, just now setting it down beside him. Only seconds had passed.

“NOW YOU WILL SEE WHY I AM KING!” his father declared.

Ulrin slowly rose to his feet, much to the shock of the supposed king. He must have thought Ulrin was too broken to get up. A moment ago, he would have been right. But now, Ulrin felt better than he had ever felt in his life. Stronger. Faster.

And angrier.

“THAT SCENT . . . WHAT HAVE YOU DONE!”

“Just taking my rightful place as a prince of Lorn,” Ulrin said. “Sorry about it being a few years late.”

The king charged at him, but Ulrin dodged. He struck the king on the back as he passed, sending him hard down to the floor. He then leaped onto the back of the king, wrapped both of his hands around his one remaining wing, and pulled. The wing slowly tore free as bones snapped and flesh tore. The king screamed out in utter agony.

King Emberlind went into a roll, and Ulrin leaped off. He landed easily, as if balance had just returned to his body. He could hardly believe how strong he had become. No wonder the Drakenblud was so sought after.

Though he had no intention of enjoying it for long. He would not allow himself to become Corrupted. Once he was done here, he was done for good.

First, he needed to finish his father.

The king let out a plume of fire, and Ulrin braced against it, trusting in the amulet. It went cold, though it was nothing compared to the ice in his veins. The heat beat against Ulrin as if he had walked into an oven, but Ulrin would not retreat from it. He put his hands in front of his face and stepped through it, walking slowly toward his father. Step by step, further into the flames, ignoring the burning of his clothes, his hair, the singing of his flesh. None of that would matter in a moment.

He reached his father and, with all of his force, punched him in the throat. The king choked, and the flames died out. The creature made a gargling noise as it tried to breathe, tried to speak, but its throat had been completely crushed.

Ulrin stepped forward, and that was when he spotted the telltale sparkle of Silverlight near his feet. He reached for the sword, thinking it was a fitting weapon to end things.

“I know you don’t like to be wielded by the Bludded,” he said as he lifted it. “That’s why you defended yourself against Gerevin. But just for one strike, let me wield you. Then you may take my life as well.”

The sword pulsed, and that silvery flowing pattern began to drip a strange liquid, but it dripped around his hand, hitting the floor with a light pitter-patter.

The king, his one eye now fully open in fear, attempted to flee. He beat the stubs of his wings, but all he accomplished was spreading more ichor from his gaping.

“Are you trying to run? Is that what a hunter does? Tell me, father, did my mother try to run? What about my siblings? Did they beg for mercy? Did you ignore their pleas because you thought they were weak? Well, I shall take your lesson for once in my life. There is no one weaker than you. Because of your weakness, you failed your family. You failed your kingdom. And now, you’ve even failed as a hunter. You’re pathetic.”

Some lingering pride must have still remained within that body, as on Ulrin’s mockery, the king charged at him for one last assault.

Ulrin struck as soon as he got close, driving the point of Silverlight directly through the king’s skull and into his brain. The sword flashed, and the head burst open in an eruption of ichor and blood.

And with that, the King of Lorn had been slain. Ulrin’s mission from all these years had been accomplished.

And now, he had just one thing left to do.

Join him.`,
